    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="roman" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Latn">
                <div type="textpart" n="1" >
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:down"/><persName><name>E<hi rend="ligature">VA</hi>LI</name><w>FILI</w><name>DEN<unclear reason="faded">O</unclear>V<hi rend="inverted">I</hi></name>
                    <lb n="2" style="text-direction:down"/><name>C<hi rend="ligature">VN</hi>IOVENDE</name>
                    <lb n="3" style="text-direction:down"/><w><hi rend="ligature">MA</hi>TEREIVS</w></persName>
                </ab>
              </div>
            </div>                  
            <div type="apparatus">
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                    <p>of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Evalus</foreign> son of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Denovus</foreign>, of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Cuniovenda</foreign> his mother</p>
                </div>
               </div>
            <div type="commentary">                    
                        <p><q>Line 1 is straightforward, consisting of the 'X son of Y' formula in the genitive case... It is unclear whether Cuniovenda was the mother of Evalus or his father, though the former is more likely. The use of the word <hi rend="italic">mater</hi> is unique amongst the early inscribed stones...</q><bibl><ptr target="EDW2007"/>Edwards 2007<citedRange unit="page">498</citedRange></bibl>. It is likely that <q>EVALI is intended as the genitive of the rare Latin name <hi rend="italic">Aevalis</hi> or a derivative <hi rend="italic">*Aevalius</hi>... The patronymic, however, is presumably Celtic, whether it is read DENOVI or DENCVI. If DENOVI is read, it may be a Welsh adaption (with British O for the Irish composition vowel A) - or a cognate - of the Irish name <hi rend="italic">*Dena-vi(ks)</hi>, 'swift fighter'... If the reading is DENCVI it may be a Welsh name in <hi rend="italic">-wy</hi> (or Latin <hi rend="italic">-uus</hi>) to the Celtic base <hi rend="italic">*denk-</hi> that is seen in Ir. <hi rend="italic">Déclán</hi>... The first element of the latter name [CVNIOVENDE] should be compared with CIIC, nos 289 CUNIA and 286 CUNEA in Ireland... rather than with the commonplace element <hi rend="italic">Cuno-</hi>, 'hound', from which it presumably derives.<bibl><ptr target="MAC1945"/>Macalister 1945<citedRange unit="page">281-284</citedRange></bibl> The composition vowel is British rather than Irish. The second element is Celtic <hi rend="italic">*-wind-</hi>, 'white' (plus Latin gen. sg. ending).</q><bibl><ptr target="EDW2007"/>Edwards 2007<citedRange unit="page">498-500</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                    </div>
